66
00:02:18,279 --> 00:02:19,519
Now, a lot of you might be asking,

67
00:02:19,519 --> 00:02:21,239
So, couldn't you just use the absolute value instead?

68
00:02:21,239 --> 00:02:23,459
So, that brings us to the question: why not just use the absolute value?

69
00:02:23,459 --> 00:02:25,799
By squaring the error, you're essentially amplifying it.

70
00:02:25,799 --> 00:02:28,359
For instance, we obviously want the error to be zero.

71
00:02:28,359 --> 00:02:30,280
But other times, my calculated error might be three.

72
00:02:30,280 --> 00:02:31,740
and when I square it, that's nine.

73
00:02:31,740 --> 00:02:33,590
So, this value actually gets bigger.

74
00:02:33,590 --> 00:02:35,990
But what if, for instance, my calculated error is 0.4?

75
00:02:35,990 --> 00:02:37,410
The difference is actually quite small already.

76
00:02:37,410 --> 00:02:40,370
So, if I square that, I get 0.16.

77
00:02:40,370 --> 00:02:41,890
This makes the error even smaller.

78
00:02:41,890 --> 00:02:45,390
This way, we're making the model more sensitive to larger errors.

79
00:02:45,390 --> 00:02:46,550
In other words, it prioritizes the big picture over minor details.

80
00:02:46,550 --> 00:02:47,760
This allows it to

81
00:02:47,760 --> 00:02:50,760
Of course, squaring the error brings another advantage.

82
00:02:50,760 --> 00:02:52,560
And its derivative is incredibly simple.

83
00:02:52,560 --> 00:02:53,520
is two times...

84
00:02:53,520 --> 00:02:54,980
which is the predicted value minus the actual value.

85
00:02:54,980 --> 00:02:56,000
So, as soon as you see this,

